Explore the Wireshark interface

Under the capture: You will see alot of options
and you will notice sparklines , which tells us that we have an active connection and it is exchanging data
Below Capture - it says "Use this filter"
You can use a capture filter, the instructor usually doesn't because it limits you to only what you are filtering, and you miss everything else


You can remove External Capture that will take off the USBPcap.
Now If we assume, with the ethernet, we don't have anything going on, as it is a wireless connection.

Looking at the USBPcap, you can see some of the devices, go into USB Input Device, select the mouse and start it.

Under capture, select Options - 
You will see three options - Input, Output and Options, where you can again select a filter for caapturing.

Enable Promiscuous mode on all interfaces
Enable monitor mode on all 802.11 interfaces

Go to Output, there you can capture to a permanent file, wireshark will save it in a temporary file until you save it.
Suppose you are running a capture run and you are putting a specific coloring rule in order to look something on the network, add that under ring buffer. The ring buffer will keep on overwriting it again and again.
(Use a ring buffer after how many files?)

Then in Options, 
Resolve MAC addresses - That would give us the manufacturer's name, simply comes from a file.
Resolve Network names - Generally, we don't select that as it would be hitting the DNS servers a lot, that would just generate alot of traffic.
Resolve transport names - It will tell us what application it thinks it is associated with.

You can select how many captures you want and then simply stop capturing.

