Tap into the Data Streams


Tap into the Network - What you see will depend on the network architecture, Two Types of Ethernet environments (Shared or Hub Based, Switched Network)

Wireless 802.11b/g/n - A hub that will allow you to see all the traffic
(If you are on Wireless network, you will go through an access point, which is acting like a hub where we can see all the traffic)

Wired on a Switch - If tapping into a wired network, you will most likely go through a switch and then you will only see your own traffic (If you want to see all the traffic, we have
choices)
        See All Traffic - Port mirroring or SPAN (Switched port analysis)
        Monitor on the device
        Full-Duplex tap in line with traffic - Need a special adapter


When you open wireshark, it displays a welcome message with a list of available network connections on your current device.
After you chooce an interface and begin the capture, the interface gathers up network traffic, all packet analysis tools work in the same way.
They gather the traffic, they decode it or break it down, and then they display it in human-readable format.
First Step - Gather the traffic , before doing this you need to have a correct capture engine, for Windows - use Npcap, for Linux - use lippcap
If you dont have the correct capture engine, you wont be able to capture the traffic

Keep in mind that traffic enters the network interface card (one frame at a time) (BITS)

Packet analysis software converts those bits into readable form for analysis

It has Source, Source Port , Destination, Destination Port, Protocol.

The heart of this is where the decoding takes place

Wireshark was Ethereal before 2006, but the main core is still the same

EPAN - Ethereal Packet Analyzer - It is the packet analyzing engine for Wireshark
